p\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver and kidneys\u003C/strong\u003E are the primary sites of gluconeogenesis in humans. The liver accounts for approximately 90% of gluconeogenesis, while the kidneys contribute about 10%. These organs contain all the necessary enzymes for the complete gluconeogenic pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall intestine and pancreas\u003C/strong\u003E - While these organs are important in glucose metabolism and regulation, they lack the complete enzyme set for gluconeogenesis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkeletal muscle and brain\u003C/strong\u003E - Despite being major glucose consumers, these tissues cannot perform gluconeogenesis due to lacking key enzymes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdipose tissue and heart\u003C/strong\u003E - These tissues are involved in energy metabolism but do not possess gluconeogenic capability\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELungs and spleen\u003C/strong\u003E - These organs have no significant role in glucose production\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the fasting state, the liver and kidneys work to maintain blood glucose levels through gluconeogenesis using substrates such as lactate, amino acids, and glycerol.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gluconeogenesis primarily occurs in the liver and kidneys using lactate, amino acids, and glycerol as substrates.","The process requires energy in the form of ATP and involves several key enzymes including pyruvate carboxylase and phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase.","Gluconeogenesis is activated during fasting states to maintain blood glucose levels."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 